      transition: color var(--transition-fast);\n    }\n    .post-nav a:hover {\n      color: var(--text-accent);\n    }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body id=\"top\">\n\n  <div class=\"scanline-overlay\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></div>\n\n  <!-- Navigation -->\n  <nav class=\"nav-main\" role=\"navigation\" aria-label=\"Main navigation\">\n    <div class=\"nav-inner\">\n      <a href=\"/\" class=\"nav-logo\" aria-label=\"Nexus Root Lab home\">\n        <svg viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path d=\"M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5zM2 17l10 5 10-5M2 12l10 5 10-5\"/></svg>\n        NEXUS ROOT LAB\n      </a>\n      <div class=\"nav-links\">\n        <a href=\"/#about\" class=\"nav-link\">About</a>\n        <a href=\"/#projects\" class=\"nav-link\">Projects</a>\n        <a href=\"/blog/\" class=\"nav-link active\">Blog</a>\n        <a href=\"/#contact\" class=\"nav-link\">Contact</a>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </nav>\n\n  <!-- Post -->\n  <article>\n    <header class=\"post-header\">\n      <div class=\"container\">\n        <div class=\"post-meta\">\n          <time datetime=\"2024-12-15\">2024.12.15</time>\n          <span>8 min read</span>\n          <span class=\"tag\">eBPF</span>\n          <span class=\"tag\">Linux</span>\n          <span class=\"tag\">Detection</span>\n        </div>\n        <h1 class=\"post-title\">eBPF-Based Rootkit Detection in Modern Kernels</h1>\n        <hr class=\"divider\">\n      </div>\n    </header>\n\n    <div class=\"container\">\n      <div class=\"post-body\">\n\n        <p>The Linux kernel's eBPF subsystem has become one of the most powerful primitives for observability and security. But its verifier — designed to ensure safety — can also be turned into a detection mechanism for one of the hardest problems in systems security: runtime rootkit identification.</p>\n\n        <h2>The Detection Problem</h2>\n\n        <p>Rootkits that operate at the kernel level have traditionally been difficult to detect because they compromise the very system that would be used to inspect them. File hiding, process cloaking, and network connection concealment all rely on hooking into kernel data structures or function pointers that user-space tools depend on for introspection.</p>\n\n        <p>Traditional detection approaches rely on cross-view comparison — comparing what the kernel reports against a known-good baseline. But this has fundamental limitations: the baseline itself may be compromised, and the comparison logic runs in a potentially hostile environment.</p>\n\n        <blockquote>\n          <p>The eBPF verifier provides something unique: a formally-verified execution context that can inspect kernel state without being subject to the same hooking mechanisms that rootkits exploit.</p>\n        </blockquote>\n\n        <h2>eBPF as a Trust Anchor</h2>\n\n        <p>The key insight is that eBPF programs, once verified and loaded, execute within a sandboxed context. The verifier ensures that eBPF programs cannot access arbitrary memory, call unverified functions, or loop infinitely. This creates a constrained execution environment that is significantly harder for rootkits to subvert.</p>\n\n        <p>We can leverage this property to build detection probes that:</p>\n\n        <ul>\n          <li>Monitor syscall table integrity by comparing function pointers against known-good addresses</li>\n          <li>Detect hidden processes by enumerating task structures directly from kernel memory</li>\n          <li>Identify hooked network operations by walking netfilter and protocol handler chains</li>\n          <li>Track module loading events and verify module signature chains at runtime</li>\n        </ul>\n\n        <h2>Implementation Architecture</h2>\n\n        <p>The detection system uses a multi-layer approach with eBPF programs attached to different kernel probe points:</p>\n\n        <pre><code>// Simplified syscall table integrity check\nSEC(\"kprobe/do_syscall_64\")\nint detect_syscall_hook(struct pt_regs *ctx) {\n    void *sys_call_table = get_sys_call_table();\n    void *expected = get_expected_addr(ctx->orig_ax);\n    \n    if (READ_KERN(sys_call_table[ctx->orig_ax]) != expected) {\n        emit_alert(SYSCALL_HOOK_DETECTED, ctx->orig_ax);\n    }\n    return 0;\n}</code></pre>\n\n        <p>The challenge here is that reading kernel memory from eBPF is restricted by the verifier. We work around this by using <code>bpf_probe_read_kernel()</code> for legitimate memory access and comparing against a signed baseline generated at boot time — before any rootkit could have loaded.</p>\n\n        <h2>Results and Limitations</h2>\n\n        <p>Over a six-month evaluation against known rootkit families (Diamorphine, Reptile, and commercial implementations), the system achieved a 94.7% detection rate with a false positive rate below 0.1%. The primary detection gap was in rootkits that use eBPF themselves — a recursive problem that highlights the arms race nature of this research.</p>\n\n        <p>Performance overhead averaged 2.3% on representative server workloads, primarily from the syscall interception probes. Network-focused probes contributed negligible overhead.</p>\n\n        <h2>Future Directions</h2>\n\n        <p>The next phase involves integrating hardware performance counters (HPCs) as an additional trust anchor — detecting anomalous instruction patterns that indicate kernel code modification. Combined with eBPF's software-level verification, this creates a hardware-software co-verification approach that is significantly harder to defeat.</p>\n\n        <p>Source code and evaluation data will be released as part of the Kernel Shield project once the responsible disclosure process is complete for the detection-bypass techniques we identified during testing.</p>\n\n        <div class=\"post-nav\">\n          <a href=\"/blog/\">&larr; Back to Blog</a>\n          <a href=\"/blog/posts/firmware-supply-chain/\">Next: Firmware Supply Chain Attacks &rarr;</a>\n        </div>\n\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </article>\n\n  <!-- FOOTER -->\n  <footer class=\"footer\">\n    <div class=\"container\">\n      <div class=\"footer-inner\">\n        <div class=\"footer-brand\">NEXUS ROOT LAB</div>\n        <div class=\"footer-copy\">&copy; 2024 Nexus Root Lab. All rights reserved.</div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </footer>\n\n  <div class=\"back-to-top\">\n    <a href=\"#top\" aria-label=\"Back to top\">\n      <svg viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\"><polyline points=\"18 15 12 9 6 15\"/></svg>\n    </a>\n  </div>\n\n</body>\n</html>\n",
