time\">8 min</span></div>\n          <h3><a href=\"/blog/posts/ebpf-rootkit-detection/\">eBPF-Based Rootkit Detection in Modern Kernels</a></h3>\n          <p class=\"blog-excerpt\">Exploring how eBPF program verification can be leveraged to detect malicious kernel modules and rootkit persistence mechanisms in real-time.</p>\n          <div class=\"blog-tags\"><span class=\"tag\">eBPF</span><span class=\"tag\">Linux</span><span class=\"tag\">Detection</span></div>\n        </article>\n        <article class=\"blog-card\">\n          <div class=\"blog-meta\"><time class=\"blog-date\" datetime=\"2024-11-28\">2024.11.28</time><span class=\"blog-read-time\">12 min</span></div>\n          <h3><a href=\"/blog/posts/firmware-supply-chain/\">Firmware Supply Chain Attacks: A Practical Analysis</a></h3>\n          <p class=\"blog-excerpt\">Case study on firmware supply chain compromise vectors in embedded devices. Analysis of three real-world incidents and defensive countermeasures.</p>\n          <div class=\"blog-tags\"><span class=\"tag\">Firmware</span><span class=\"tag\">Supply Chain</span></div>\n        </article>\n        <article class=\"blog-card\">\n          <div class=\"blog-meta\"><time class=\"blog-date\" datetime=\"2024-10-03\">2024.10.03</time><span class=\"blog-read-time\">6 min</span></div>\n          <h3><a href=\"#\">The Evolution of ROP Chains Post-RET</a></h3>\n          <p class=\"blog-excerpt\">From classical ROP to JOP and COP: tracing the evolution of code-reuse attacks and the never-ending arms race with control-flow integrity defenses.</p>\n          <div class=\"blog-tags\"><span class=\"tag\">Exploitation</span><span class=\"tag\">ROP</span><span class=\"tag\">Mitigation</span></div>\n        </article>\n        <article class=\"blog-card\">\n          <div class=\"blog-meta\"><time class=\"blog-date\" datetime=\"2024-09-19\">2024.09.19</time><span class=\"blog-read-time\">10 min</span></div>\n          <h3><a href=\"#\">Attack Surface of Confidential Computing Enclaves</a></h3>\n          <p class=\"blog-excerpt\">Mapping the trust boundaries and attack surfaces of TEE implementations — from SGX to ARM TrustZone and emerging RISC-V enclaves.</p>\n          <div class=\"blog-tags\"><span class=\"tag\">TEE</span><span class=\"tag\">SGX</span><span class=\"tag\">Hardware</span></div>\n        </article>\n        <article class=\"blog-card\">\n          <div class=\"blog-meta\"><time class=\"blog-date\" datetime=\"2024-08-05\">2024.08.05</time><span class=\"blog-read-time\">7 min</span></div>\n          <h3><a href=\"#\">Can Rust Save Us? A Realistic Look at Memory Safety</a></h3>\n          <p class=\"blog-excerpt\">Examining the actual security impact of Rust adoption in systems code — beyond the hype, looking at CVE data and real-world exploitability reductions.</p>\n          <div class=\"blog-tags\"><span class=\"tag\">Rust</span><span class=\"tag\">Memory Safety</span><span class=\"tag\">Analysis</span></div>\n        </article>\n        <article class=\"blog-card\">\n          <div class=\"blog-meta\"><time class=\"blog-date\" datetime=\"2024-07-22\">2024.07.22</time><span class=\"blog-read-time\">9 min</span></div>\n          <h3><a href=\"#\">A Taxonomy of Network Covert Channels</a></h3>\n          <p class=\"blog-excerpt\">Systematic classification of covert communication methods — timing channels, storage channels, and protocol manipulation techniques for C2 evasion.</p>\n          <div class=\"blog-tags\"><span class=\"tag\">Covert Channels</span><span class=\"tag\">Networking</span><span class=\"tag\">C2</span></div>\n        </article>\n        <article class=\"blog-card\">\n          <div class=\"blog-meta\"><time class=\"blog-date\" datetime=\"2024-06-10\">2024.06.10</time><span class=\"blog-read-time\">5 min</span></div>\n          <h3><a href=\"#\">BPF Verifier Bypass Techniques: A Survey</a></h3>\n          <p class=\"blog-excerpt\">Cataloging known techniques for bypassing the eBPF verifier — from Spectre-based primitives to type confusion in map operations.</p>\n          <div class=\"blog-tags\"><span class=\"tag\">eBPF</span><span class=\"tag\">Exploitation</span><span class=\"tag\">Kernel</span></div>\n        </article>\n        <article class=\"blog-card\">\n          <div class=\"blog-meta\"><time class=\"blog-date\" datetime=\"2024-05-01\">2024.05.01</time><span class=\"blog-read-time\">11 min</span></div>\n          <h3><a href=\"#\">The Resurgence of DMA Attacks in the Thunderbolt Era</a></h3>\n          <p class=\"blog-excerpt\">How USB4 and Thunderbolt 4 have reopened direct memory access attack vectors, and why IOMMU configurations still fail in practice.</p>\n          <div class=\"blog-tags\"><span class=\"tag\">DMA</span><span class=\"tag\">Hardware</span><span class=\"tag\">Thunderbolt</span></div>\n        </article>\n        <article class=\"blog-card\">\n          <div class=\"blog-meta\"><time class=\"blog-date\" datetime=\"2024-03-18\">2024.03.18</time><span class=\"blog-read-time\">8 min</span></div>\n          <h3><a href=\"#\">Coverage-Guided Kernel Fuzzing: What Actually Works</a></h3>\n          <p class=\"blog-excerpt\">Practical comparison of Syzkaller, kAFL, and custom fuzzers for Linux kernel vulnerability discovery — results from 6 months of continuous fuzzing campaigns.</p>\n          <div class=\"blog-tags\"><span class=\"tag\">Fuzzing</span><span class=\"tag\">Kernel</span><span class=\"tag\">Tools</span></div>\n        </article>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <footer class=\"footer\">\n    <div class=\"container\">\n      <div class=\"footer-inner\">\n        <div class=\"footer-brand\">NEXUS ROOT LAB</div>\n        <div class=\"footer-copy\">&copy; 2024 Nexus Root Lab. All rights reserved.</div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </footer>\n  <div class=\"back-to-top\"><a href=\"#top\" aria-label=\"Back to top\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\"><polyline points=\"18 15 12 9 6 15\"/></svg></a></div>\n</body>\n</html>\n",
